# Linux Process & Network Management + Architecture Concepts

---

## Process Management

### Real-life Analogy (Hierarchy)

```
TM â†’ TL â†’ Senior â†’ Junior â†’ Fresher
```

* TM assigns tasks to TLs
* TL distributes work further
* Same hierarchy applies to **parent and child processes** in Linux

---

## How a Command Works Internally

Example:

```
ls -l
```

Flow:

1. Command is executed by user
2. A **process is created**
3. Kernel assigns a **PID (Process ID)**
4. Command is executed in kernel
5. Output is returned
6. Result is displayed on screen

---

## ps Command

```
ps
```

Sample output fields:

```
UID   PID   PPID   C   STIME   TTY   TIME   CMD
```

### Important Columns

* **PID** â†’ Process ID
* **PPID** â†’ Parent Process ID

---

## List Processes

```
ps -ef
ps -ef | grep <process-name>
```

---

## Foreground & Background Processes

* Foreground â†’ Runs in terminal
* Background â†’ Runs behind terminal

```
command &
```

---

## Kill a Process

```
kill <PID>        â†’ Graceful termination (SIGTERM)
kill -9 <PID>     â†’ Force kill (SIGKILL)
```

---

## Service & Process Relation

```
systemctl status nginx
ps -ef | grep nginx
```

* Application runs as a **process**
* Each process has a **PID**

---

## Resource Usage

Example:

* 10 users â†’ ~0.1% CPU, ~0.1% RAM
* 2000 users â†’ ~10% CPU, ~20% RAM

Check resource usage of a specific process:

```
top -p <PID>
```

---

## Network Management

### Check Open Ports in Linux

```
netstat -lntp
```

Common workflow:

```
systemctl status <service>
ps -ef | grep <service>
netstat -lntp
top -p <PID>
```

---

## 3-Tier Architecture

### Desktop Application Problems

* High resource usage
* Application hang issues
* Manual installation & upgrades
* Storage limitations
* Compatibility issues
* No proper data security or backup
* Cannot access from anywhere

ðŸ‘‰ Hence, **architecture is important**

---

## Real-Life Architecture Examples

### Roadside Breakfast Shop

* Single person handles:

  * Order
  * Cooking
  * Serving
  * Payment
* Works only for < 10 customers

---

### Small Hotel

* Cook â†’ prepares items
* Owner â†’ handles counter & tokens
* Around 20â€“100 members

---

### Restaurant (3-Tier Model)

* Captain â†’ welcomes customers
* Waiter â†’ takes orders
* Chef â†’ prepares food
* Waiter â†’ garnishing & serving

Benefits:

1. Security
2. Queue management (better taste & efficiency)

---

---

## Common Tools Used

* Visual Studio Code
* PuTTY
* Terraform
* AWS CLI v2

