# MySQL, Proxy, HTTP & Server Configuration Notes

## MySQL

MySQL is an RDBMS (Relational Database Management System)  
Data is stored in tables and columns

Linux Server â†’ MySQL Server

### MySQL Architecture (Analogy)

House â†’ Linux Server  
Room â†’ Database Server  
Rack â†’ Schema  
Items â†’ Tables  

- One DB server can have one or many databases
- Supports transactions, users, permissions

---

## MySQL Connectivity Test

telnet mysql.daws84s.site 3306

Purpose:
- Check whether MySQL is running
- Check whether port 3306 is open
- Check whether MySQL is accepting connections

If connected but issues exist:
- User / password problem
- Query / permission problem

---

## Nginx Configuration

Main configuration file:
/etc/nginx/nginx.conf

Nginx can act as:
- Web server
- Reverse proxy
- Load balancer

---

## Client and Server

- Server â†’ Prime server
- Client â†’ VPN / Mobile / Browser

---

## Forward Proxy

Client identity is hidden from server

Flow:
Actual Client â†’ Forward Proxy â†’ Server

Use cases:
1. Content filtering
2. Traffic monitoring
3. Anonymous client access
4. Geo-restriction bypass
5. Caching

---

## Reverse Proxy

Client is not aware of backend server identity

Flow:
Client â†’ Reverse Proxy â†’ Backend Server

Benefits:
1. Security
2. Load balancing
3. SSL termination
4. Backend abstraction

Nginx is commonly used as a reverse proxy

---

## Frontend and Backend

Frontend communicates with backend APIs

Backend connectivity test:
telnet backend.daws84s.site 8080

Backend troubleshooting:
- Login to backend server
- Check service status:
  systemctl status backend
- Check logs:
  /var/log

Example API:
http://aws.site/api/transaction

---

## HTTP Status Codes

1XX â†’ Informational  
2XX â†’ Success  
3XX â†’ Redirection  

Errors:
4XX â†’ Client-side error  
5XX â†’ Server-side error  

---

## CRUD Operations

INSERT  
SELECT  
UPDATE  
DELETE  

